    <li class="comment odd alt depth-5" id="dsq-comment-250">
        <div id="dsq-comment-header-250" class="dsq-comment-header">
            <cite id="dsq-cite-250">
                <span id="dsq-author-user-250">nope</span>
            </cite>
        </div>
        <div id="dsq-comment-body-250" class="dsq-comment-body">
            <div id="dsq-comment-message-250" class="dsq-comment-message"><p>don&#8217;t bother, guy doesn&#8217;t know what he&#8217;s talking about. Even in my math above that assumes the network gains ZERO except for one miner suddenly. In fact the order of power gain would be higher because it would have to make up for the rest of the network gain.</p>
<p>(attackerOriginalRate+attackerRateGain+otherNetworkGain) / (networkOriginalRate+attackerRateGain+otherNetworkGain) = .51</p>
<p>A+B+C / D+B+C = .51</p>
<p>A+B+C = .51D+.51B+.51C</p>
<p>B = .51D-A+.51B-.49C</p>
<p>-.49B=.51D-A-.49C</p>
<p>B = -.49(.51D-A-.49C)</p>
<p>B = .49A &#8211; .2499D + .2401C</p>
<p>plug in any values for original rates and what the network gains to see how insane it would be to suddenly be 51% of the network. Nope.</p>
